<H2><U>
Bootup Stories
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.indigenouspeople.net/foundsum.htm
">How Glooscap Found Summer</a>:</b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.mun.ca/rels/native/micmac/mic4.html
">Glooscap and the Wizard</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Wabanaki Indian stories in which the culture hero tricks Bootup, then repays the whale with a pipe to smoke.
<BR>

<H2><U>
Recommended Books of Related Native American Legends</a>

</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1888034017/natilangofthe-20
">Giants of the Dawnland</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A good collection of Wabanaki Indian legends told by a Penobscot author. 
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1885772254/natilangofthe-20
">Seven Eyes, Seven Legs</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
More good Wabanaki myths and folktales told and illustrated by an Abenaki Indian author. 
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1555911277/natilangofthe-20
">Native American Animal Stories</A></B>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Excellent collection of American Indian tales about animals, told by an Abenaki storyteller.
<BR>


